Cardiac output during cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) in a nonpregnant patient is approximately 30%. The fact that approximately 17% of a pregnant patient’s cardiac output is diverted to the uterus suggests that blood flow to vital organs is significantly limited during CPR in the pregnant patient. There has therefore been much interest in determining ways to decrease the impact of the gravid uterus on cardiac output. One study, using a mannequin, looked at angles at which the maximal force could be achieved and found that 80% of the supine force was achieved at an angle of 27°, and advocated the use of a Cardiff wedge (Figure 1
)—a device that places the patient at 27° while providing a firm support on which to perform CPR.27 The use of a Cardiff wedge, foam wedge, or human wedge was therefore advised. The human wedge (Figure 2
) is an alternative to the Cardiff wedge. It can be performed by having a member of the team kneel next to the patient, with the patient’s back on the human wedge’s thighs. The human wedge can then place a hand on the patient’s shoulder and the other on her pelvis to help stabilize her during resuscitation. The advantage of the human wedge is that it can be performed by an untrained person and does not require any equipment. The disadvantage of this wedge is that uterine displacement needs to be interrupted during defibrillation with repositioning between defibrillation attempts.

Other.Other indirect causes of maternal mortality (see Table 4
) include trauma, psychiatric disease, chronic hypertension (possibly by causing a hypertensive cardiomyopathy), and cerebrovascular disease.3,24,77 Interestingly, CEMACH found that the presence of obesity, especially morbid obesity, increased the risk of both direct and indirect causes of mortality (Table 5
).
